15. ultra: sc. Bosphorum.

16. caeca...fata: for the grouping with intrusive timet see on P. 46 a.

17. celerem (p) i.e. ‘the swiftness (of flight)' ; see on P. 27. It may be that celerem is ἀπὸ κοινοῦ with sagittas and sugam (see on P. 33), but the phrase looks like an awkward reminiscence of Odes 2. 7. 9, and Bentley’s reducem is tempting, for the preposited adjective gives point to the oxymoron (see on Epod. 5. 82).

17, 18. celerem fugam Ι Parthi: for the grouping see on P. 35.

18. Parthi, by position, has stress (see on Odes 4. 9. 26>; its position helps out this curious series of artificial antitheses i.e. the Poenus fears the Bosporus, the Roman fears the Parthian, and the Parthian fears a Roman prison. For a similar but terser effort see Odes 3. 6. 46-48.

18, 19. Italum is ἀπὸ κοινοῦ with catenas and rabum see on P. 33.

19. robur has stress (see on Odes 4. 9. 26). Its very position seems to suggest the finality of a life sentence. Compare custos at Odes 3. 4. 79.

20. gentis: for its position see on Odes 1. 3. 16.

21. quarn paene goes with the whole sentence (see on odes 2. 9. 13). Contrast paene at Odes 3. 6. 13.

furvae regna Proserpinae: for the grouping see on P. 20 ιι.
